{"/service/ndnp/nn/batch_nn_quarterman_ver03/data/sn83030273/00212474575/1920092101/0353.xml":{"full_text":"THE SUN AND NEW YORK HERALD, TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 21, 1920,\n9\n1\nII, S. IS BEST OFF\nOF ALL NATIONS,\nDECLARES LANE\nOn Pound Economic Ttnsis,\nWith Plenty of Jtnw\nMaterials,\nIS WOTIK FOR ALL\nTrade Outlook for Winter\nflood. Both Hetail and\nWholesale.\nn. T-. C. STILL UNSOLVED\nFormer Secretory Has First\nllnnd Reports From All\nOver Country.\nHMrt of gvnci) Is offered to those\ntho concslv that tho country Is Rolnc\nto th doss In a report Issued yester\nby Franklin 1C. Lone, foiWrly\nSKretary of tho Interior, In width he\nlt,vf the result of etntlaticn Ruthfrcl\nfioni every corner of tho UnltM 8ttr\nrenctrnlnff thn lndustrls.1, agricultural,\nfinancial nnd polltlcul condition!\nthroughout the country.\nMr. L.ano gathered htn material\nthrough the aid of 900 field represent\natlves of tho Fidelity and Deposit\nCompany of Maryland and seta forth\nthat while the com of living U Mill an\nunsolved problem the country la on a\nsound economic: basis, with the wave\nof extravagance subsiding. He adds\ntMt ravine I\" IfttTeaslrwj, that whole\ntalera and retallern are optimistic\nover the winter outlook and that there\nH n jTowlnp disposition for steady\nnork, ntthouRh the Individual pro\ni.jeilvlty of labor Ik not yet showing\nrr .n h evidence of Inercnso.\nHe rays the problem of the cost of\n'iMrj j outstanding and doen not recm\nt .vi receiving fiom lh lvo principal\npolitical psrtlea the attention It de\nfirves. Itut he adds that, wit- tho coun\nts economically sound tho way It is,\nlure In a s.niral spirit of confidence In\nthe future, regardless of the irrult of\nUi rlcotlon.\nVndsr the heading of Industrial con\nations Mr. Lane saya:\n\"EconomlSAlly the United States Is\nhown to be better off than any other\nA Promise By\nThe American Tobacco Company\nIt\nIll Filth Avenue,\nNew York, N. Y.\ncountry In the world. Thsrs U no nU\n1 nee of Idlsness, our people hare the\nopportunity to work and are at work.\n\"Tilers Is no shortage of raw material\nsufficient to curtail production reported\nfrom any of the nine geographical dls-\niricia into which the country was d\nvlded for tho purpose of survey, Only In\ntht district Including Minnesota, the Da.\nMas, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska and Wis.\nconsln Is there evidence of a lack of\norders, tfew England Industries report\na number of cancellations, tut there, as\neieswnere, msnusaoiurars are well filled\nwith calls for their jroducte,\nTransportation llettrr,\n\"Transportation conditions nre Im\nproving everywhere and a substantial\nreduction In the freight rsr shortage Ik\nrprtrd In every district except In the\nnocky Mountsln States, In the flouth.\nwest and In the dMrlct Including Hen\ntucky, Tennessee. Alsbsma nnd Miuii.\nflppl, although an Improvement it. noted\nin ins latter district.\n\"A Shorties of coal and tha falhira nt\nUbor to Increase Individual productivity\nappear to be the only two unfavorable\naspects In ths Immediate Industrial situ.\notfon. The Ilocky Mountain and Taclflo\nnisisa report a sufficient supply of fuel,\nviii owsr sections or tns country are\nfeeling the shortage, but It la appar\nently least felt by the South Atlantic\nflutes.\n\"Although labor Is coatlnr still more\nthan It did Isst year, It apparently Is\nproducing no mor. Wsgcs have ad\nvanced from 10 to JO per cent, In the\nlast twelve months and yet nowhere la\nthere reported Increase In productivity\nper man, I am not expecting that the\ncost of labor will fall off even In Ih6\nworst of times to Its pre-wsr stage, for\nI believe that the real differential be\ntween directing labor and manual labor\nw never again be a great as It lias\nbeen.\n\"Ho far as the dletrlbutlon of labor\nIs concerned, the sltustlon nationally ap\npthrs to be well equalised. A shortage\nof labor la found only In the Middle and\nFouth Atlantic States and thle Is largely\nof unskilled workers. In the rest of the\ncountry the demand and supply appear\nbalanced. Only In some sections of the\nMiddle Atlantic States la any unemploy\nment reported and this Is In certain of\nth( skilled trades, chiefly the building\nand shipbuilding trades,\nIfuustna? Mtaatlon,\n\"An Important disclosure of the sur\nety Is the seriousness of the housing\nsituation, In many of the larger Indus\ntrial centres where the snorts e has been\nmost acute, the Investigation of the\nFidelity and Uepnslt Company has die-\ncioied building operstlons to be decreas\ning Instead or inncsslng.\nThe call for buildings comes loudest\nfrom the m'fst essential plarwt of manu\nfacture rather than from the retail cen\ntres, and la for low priced dwellings.\nnulldlnr construction Is Increasing In\nNew Zntrland, but the bulk of th con\nstruction Is of factories, warehouses and\netores. New Vork, Pennsylvania and\nmost of the other great Industrial State\n\"f the East and mlddl West show a fall\ning off In building operations. There Is\nImprovement In the housing situation In\nSouthern and I'selflc coast Industrial\ncentres, with special emphasis on the\nerection of workmen's home.\n\"In no section of the country did the\nimestlgators find sentiment In favor of\nGovernment ownership of the railroads:\nWalk Into Any Store In\nThe United States To-Day\nAnd Try The Lord Salisbury\nTurkish Cigarette. Should\nIt Not Appeal To Your Taste,\nThe Clerk Will Han, d You Back\nYour Money On The Spot.\nWill Pay\nleosssstio\nIf It Should Happen That A Dealer Refuses To Carry\nOut Our Offer, Send The Open Package With The Remain\ning Cigarettes, To The Main Office Of The American\nTobacco Company, III Fifth Ave., New York City,\nWith Your Name And Address Plainly Written And We\nWill Send You Our Check For The Amount You Spent!\nnd I everywhere' better transportation\nwimiiiun ire reported,\n\"Agriculture Is isntrillv reeomlsed\nas -the backbone of the country, and the\nfarming situation Is excellent from no\nociign nas an unravorawe report been\nreceived, Our farmers appear every\nwhsrs to be In too happy a mood to per.\nmlt at this time Die cynicism, 'the far\nmer Is always grumbling,' They are\nwell supplied with funds from the sals\nsaie or this year's crops, but they are\nwise In that they know more favorable\nmarketing conditions can be created,\n\"The recent drop In gram prices Is\nreported to have had no effect except in\nthe Ilocky Mountain flutes, Farmers of\nIllinois, Indiana, Michigan, Wisconsin\nnnd other Central Hlates are withholding\ngrain,\n\"In tho financial field money Is tight\nThat may mean several things first,\nthat the people wont money badly to\nput Into producing activities) second,\nthat thn banks attempt tn get whatever\nthe trafTIo will bear, shearing close to\nths skin: third, that there Is an Inade\nquate supply of money) or, fourth, that\nthose who have money lack confidence.\n\"There are other reasons, no doubt,\nand among them that as the dollar now\nbuys less than heretoforce people with\nmoney wish to charge reore for the ser\nvice that money gives. No one can an\neurately say which of these causes I\nhe most important factor, but prob\nably all contribute to the present situa\ntion, \"The telegraphic reports from every\nsection of the country state that th\"\nbanka are well loaned up, nlthough\nmoney la available In the East and Cen\ntral districts at from six to eight per\ncent. Interest. The Southwest, nocky\nMountain and Pacific mates report the\nhighest Interest rates, averaging from\nto 10 per cent., and In the Mountain dls\ntrict ns high as 12 per cent.\nThere Is great encouragement, how\never, to be drawn from the fact that\nIn only one of the nine geographical 01.\nvlilons, the Ilocky Mountain, has there\n,been a decrraee In bank deposits during\nme ion i six monuis, wnne me general\nIncrease Includes corporation deposits,\nIndividual savings accounts shows a\nmore marked Improvement everywhere,\nThis seems to show clearly that the\norgy of spending and extravagance la\nover.\nIlUcoantlnn Is General,\n\"Discounting of bills by Industrial\nconcerns is universally reported, ex\ncept in the Middle Atlantic, Southwestern\nand I'selflc coast States, manufacturers\nappear to be carrying large amount of\ncustomers' psper.\nThe country doea not like the present\ntaxation system. The excess profits tax\nIs In bad favor everywhere. Opinion Is\ndivided, however, as to a substitute\nIn the Cast and central Went sentiment\nrune strongly for a sales tax, hut else\nwhere opinion as to a substitute la di\nvided.\n\"Wo ar not yet masters of the art of\ndistribution of products. Tho fact thst\nthtf farmers uniformly report m desire for\nroino cooperative method by which their\nproduct can bo brought to consumers\nmeans that this problem Is of the great-!\nem importance, uui n is noi lor me\nfarmers' benefit primarily that such a\nmovement must quickly culminate In\naction. The consumer feels that some\nwhere between the farmer and himself\ntoo much Is taken for a service of com-\npa rat I ve Insignificance In contrast with j\nif 1\nYou To Try\nwhich means that if you don't like LORD SALISBURY\nCigarettes you can get your money back from the dealer.\nthat which the producer himself renders,\n\"The farmer apparently are not\nalone In desiring cooperative action.\nThe survey shows opposition to co\noperative movements only In the New\nKngland and Paclflo coast districts. Oen\ntlmsnt Is divided In Ohio, Illinois and\nthe othsr North Csntral Western mates,\nbut favorable In ths Middle Atlantic, the\nBouth Central and the llouthern Btates.\n\"Politically the replies Indicate thst\nIt Is too early to tell what the outcome\nOf the November slectton will be. Three\nmonths ago there was a stronger\npublican sentlmsnt than there appears\nto be now. The trend has been, and .Is,\nRepublican, What It will be tn Novcny\nbar these gentlemen do not prophesy,\n'The large outstanding fact devsl.\noped by the Fidelity and Deposit Com\npany seems to be that the greatest Issue\nIn the publlo mind Is being overlooked\nby the campaigners the high cost of\nliving. I think this conclusion might\nwell be Juitlfled, but the blame should\nnot be cast upon the producer, and cer\ntainly the farmer haa not received his\nshare of the wealth which he creates.\n'The cost of living and foreign rela\nlions seem to be the main Issues. Taxa.\ntlon nnd Industrial relatione also occupy\na plsce In the general political thought.\nLat Interest appears lo be shown In\nthe rsllroad policy of the preeenl Ad\nministration, radical movements and\nprohibition.\n\"It Is clear, thst the country Is on\nround economic basis, nnd there Is gen\nerally a spirit of confidence In the fu\nture, regsrdlesa of Ihe outcome of the\nelection,\n\"The business outlook appears to be\ngood In every section. Wholesalers and\nretailers view the fall and winter opti\nmistically. The retailer Is finding that\nthe consumer Is looking forward without\nfear to the winter, and his purchases\nfrom the wholesaler are founded upon\nthis optimism. From Ihe simple toller\nup through the tradesman to the Indus\ntry and the financier there runs Uie\nconnected feeling of confidence.\"\nTENN ESS EE A NS SEEK\nTO HALT SUFFRAGE\nAsk Secretary Colby to With\ndraw Proclamation.\ntfnal f,i Tits Sex txt Ntw Vosa IltittD.\nWashington. Sept. CO. Tennessee\nsuffrage opponents, headed by Seth\nWalker. Speaker of the Lower House\nof the Leglslsture, to-day saw Secretary\nof State Colby and asked him to with\ndraw his proclamation of the Federal\nWoman Suffrage amendment.\nThe delegation nld It was the firm\nbelief of Hi members that suffrage had\nbeen ratified In Tennessee In violation\nof the State constitution and the estab\nlished rules of the legislature, It was\nbelieved they got little satlifactlon.\nTlio proclamation of the suffrage\namendment could be withdrawn now\ninn inc turirage amendment still stand j\nas the law of the land, since Connuctl-\ncm nun ran lira, wutarawai or, tne i\nproclamation, however, and Issuance of\nn new one would mean that the ratifica\ntion of a Democratic State would not\nappear thereon and that a Republican\nStote would tie substituted for It. Tills\nfsct. with legal advice received by Mr.\nColby, probably will prevent any further\naction on his part.\nit- \"MS\nf t r\n\nMIDWEST CLINCHED\nBY REPUBLICANS\nHorry Dougherty 'Roys Ohio\nWill Give Hording Pluwl\nity of 00,000.\nBANKS ON OTHER STATES\nScnntor Elklnn After Study of\nConditions Confildorfl West\nVirginia Is Safe.\nThat Harding la certain to carry all\nths middle Western States was the news\nbrought to nepubllean National Com\nmittee headquarters yesterday from a\nnumber of tources,\nHarry Dougherty, manager of Har\nding's pre-conventlnn campaign, who\nlli be hre for several days, said that\nhe Is certain the Itepubllcan nomine\nwill sweep the middle st In Ohio,\nhe predicted, hie plurality will be at\nleast as large on was that of president\nWilson, which was more than il,U00,\nHe feels that Indiana Is safely Itepub\nllcan and that Kentucky and Missouri\nalso will te found In the nepubllean\ncolumn. The Lowden-Thompeon rum\npu In Illinois, he declared, haa not\naffected the certainty of the Itepubllcan\nvictory there next November for Ihe\nreason that the national organisation\nhas not mixed In the local altuuion one\nway or the other and both sides of the\nfactional fight are for Harding,\nCommenting on Democrat It: claims\nthat Gov. Cox Is responsible for the\nwcrkmen's compensation law In Ohio,\nand, therefore, ould get a large vote\namong tho miner. Mr, Dougherty Mid:\n\"Mr. Cox wss not Governor when the\nworkmen's compensation law was passed\nany mora than he was Governor when\nthe Ten Commandments were made,\"\nDavis Elklns, United States Senator\nfrom West Virginia, was a visitor at na\nTo\nCAREFUL truck owners are\nfiguring their costs pretty\nclosely these' days- tire costs\nalong with the others.\nIt is no longer \"clap on a new\ntire and hang the expense.\" At\nleast, not with the owners we\ncome in contact with.\nService, wear, traction,\ncushioning qualities, construc\ntion are coming to mean more\nthan they used to, not only to\nowners but to drivers of motor\ntrucks.\nAnd the more they mean, the\nmore we find truck owners and\noperators turning to the new\nUnited States Grainless Rubber\nSolid Truck Tire.\ni\nSIMONSEN\ntional Itepubllcan headquarters yester\nday, He said that a close study of con.\ndltlons In West Virginia makes It cer\ntain that Harding and Coolldge wll get\ntan electoral vote of that State by a\nsubstantial majority, fleno'tor Klklns U\na son of the late Senator Stephen p.\nFlklns and was elected to the Henato\nwMIe he was absent from this country,\nserving In France.\ni p.i.ni .n., nr iha IlaDubllran.\nConrreealonal Committee was opened\nyesterday ot nepuoncan nauoni wm\ni,..n.,r. with Itonresenta-\nlive A. n, Houghton of Corning, N. V..\nnnd liepresentative jonn si.\nNew Haven, Conn., in charge. The New\nYork ofllco will ict a a clearing house\nfor printed Information and \"directive\nenergy\" for the campaigns In the Con\nji.t.iifl in tit vjnt. With tnft\nopenlnK of this branch the Concessional\ncampaign may be consider! In Jul1\nswing nepresentatlve Simeon D, Fess\nof Ohio Is chairman of the Congressional\ncommittee, which nas omcre i i\",\nWashington end Chicago,\nITALIAN REPUBLICANS\nREPUDIATE LEAGUE\nAlso Resentful of Wilton's\nTreatment of Fiume.\nThe Italian American nepubllean\nleague, In session yesterday with rep\nresentatives from twenty-three States,\nmsde Its plana to solidify the sentiment\nof votera of Italian oflgln In favor of\nSenator Harding and Oov. Coolldge In\nthe November election. Committees\nwere named also to organise the women\nvoters of Italian origin.\nOne of the first official acts of the\nconvention was the adoption by the res\nolutlons committee of a resolution re\npudiating the League of Nations. The\nresolution, which was drafted by Judge\nFrond A. I'